<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%">
<tr>
	<td width="1%">&nbsp;</td>
	<td width="98%">
  
		<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%">
		<tr>
		    <td valign="top">
		     <p><font face="Verdana" size="3"><b>Article Title:</b>&nbsp;</font>
		     <font face="Verdana" size="2">A few Abashi posts from the gameplay board</font><br>
		     <a href = "../Subscribe.asp?DID=170601" ><font face="Verdana" size="2">[Subscribe to this document]</font></a></p>
			 </td>
		</tr>
		
		<tr><td>&nbsp;</tr><tr>
		
		    <td valign="top"><div style= "padding:4;float: right"> <script language=JavaScript src=http://www.obsidian-tech.com/absolutebm/abmx.aspx?z=26></script></div><p><font face="Verdana" size="2">
		    <Blockquote>
<B><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum4/HTML/059457.html">ABASHI - YOU FLAT OUT LIED. NO IFS ANDS OR BUTTS! Check this out....</a></B><P>

QUOTE<BR>
<I>I know you've been following this issue for some time, so I'll keep it short. They aren't broken. Increasing the level-ranged experience requirement causes a need to make up experinece in the first level of the new range. Perhaps we should have spread out that additional XP requirement over the 5 levels of the range, but the same amount of experience would be required regardless.
Merely doubling the xpgain or halving the xploss in the hell level, or the level after respectively doesn't "fix" the issue, it just makes it faster to get through those levels. <P>

Though I appreciate everyone's opinion on the matter, the experience system is *absolutely not* subject to post-production changes. Leveling works as it has always worked, and will continue to work in the same fashion. <P>

-Gordon</I><BR>
END QUOTE<P>

I really didn't believe it till I saw it with my own eyes. Your entire quoted post above is a lie. I wish I had saved the original thread in which you answered my question about hell levels. You stated *point-blank* that hell levels were a *KNOWN BUG* but you all refused to fix them mostly due to players receiving an extra level or two if you fixed them.<P>

Which is it Abashi? What's the story? Why the complete change in answers?<P>

<B>Brent, <P>

If you can quote something from late December/Early January, I would think that you could have found this from March. Pay close attention to the first paragraph. As for what I said in January, though I certainly never said it was a bug, you've got me for a bad choice of words on "fixing". Perhaps I should have said "changing". In any case, the subject is closed. If you are going to call someone a liar at least have the common courtesy to get your data right:</B><P>

Abashi clearly said some time ago that hell levels are a bug in code<P>

<B>Given my time here at Verant, I think I can finally articulate this in a more accurate manner. I think "bug" is probably not the correct term to describe why hell levels are there. "Unintended Mathematical Consequence" would probably be a better description. Trying to put it in easy terms:<P>

Basically, everyone knows that the experience needed at every level is a curve. Well, it's not so much a curve, as it is a series of straight lines. As you level, the "curve" gets steeper. However, due to the formula used, in the first level after the curve gets steeper, you must "make up" all of the experience as if the curve had been that steep all along. As such, a "Hell Level" is the first level where a new experience curve took affect. Ideally, it would have been nice if the formula spread the additional experience required over all the levels of the next range, rather than requiring it all in one level, but the outcome is the same.<P>

As for 50+, it's probably safe to say that experience required in those levels won't be on the same curve as 45-50, and as such, any time the curve steepens, the "Hell Level Phenomenon" will be present for the first level of the new curve.<P>

Basically, this is just the way it is, and we won't be readjusting the experience curves. They haven't been changed since release, and no one ever said that progression would be linear.<P> 

-Gordon</B><P>

<HR align="center" width="75%"><P>

<B><a href="http://boards.station.sony.com/everquest/Forum4/HTML/059507.html">Posted this 2 hours ago...</a></B><P>

Umm, abashi.... What if you have more than 8 keys on you and they're nodrop... And they respawn, but you have 8 slots... Eh?<P>

<B>Hmmm, good question. My money is on them disappearing. Since there are only 3 keys, and since they spawn with you when you die, there'd really be no reason for someone to have 8 on them IMHO. <P>

I would however recommend that if you have 8 keys that you do not have them all on you upon death after the next patch.</B><P>

Gordon, are you saying that Verant this is the full notice Verant is giving to the players on those servers? Three hours? What about people that are on vacation because of the U.S. holiday? Or those that just don't happen to play on Wednesdays? Or those that don't read Forums? Do you consider this sufficient time for guilds to learn about this and to try to contact members? even if they discussed it in advance, without knowing the date and time of the move, they won't be able to coordinate their transfers.<P>

<B>We'll have registration open all night, giving most that are willing the chance to register. As for the idea of possibly splitting up guilds, that is a danger with all moves. There's no guarantee that if everyone in the guild runs the command that they'll all get moved.<P>

Finally, I did announce last week that we'd be doing the split this week, so I think that more are prepared than you might think. All of that said, we'll certainly do everything in our power to help those that are split up in the process.</B><P>

In the next patch, keys for Charasis, Sebilis, and Howling Stones will all be made NODROP if not currently set with that flag." *ahem* Howling Stones IS Charasis..(it has two names for some reason)<P>

<B>Ack! Well I meant Veeshan's Peak. Of course, keys for Sebilis and VP are already NODROP, so the main concern was Charasis (Howling Stones). So I guess I got it covered. </B><P>

ack! Abashi - wait! How come the new server doesn't have a name beginning with an "A" !! Bertoxx is going to be right back in the same boat in a month! Or are you going to "cap" us? (that's what I hope) <P>

<B>New users get the old sort order (ascending order by population) until they choose something different. The server selection UI keeps track of the last sort-order selected. <P>

Only people that came on new between Kunark launching and us fixing the sort order got the alpha order by default. I'm hoping that existing people starting new characters understand the inverse correlation between server population and gameplay, to a certain threshold.<P>

-Gordon</B>
</blockquote>
		    </font></p>
			 </td>
		</tr>
